# Research Interests — Scorer Grounding

This file is injected verbatim into the system prompt that scores each ingested
paper. Edit it whenever YOUR stack changes shape. The scorer reads it on every
run.

The scorer asks: "could this technique upgrade one of the user's existing
systems?" — and uses the system slugs you define here in its `applies_to` field.

---

## My systems (slugs the scorer uses in `applies_to`)

Edit this list to match what you actually run. Each slug should be a short
identifier (snake-case is conventional). Add a one-line description so the
scorer can reason about applicability.

- **`my-rag`** — semantic search pipeline over my notes. Currently uses
  nomic-embed-text + Qdrant. ~50k chunks, source-filtered queries.
- **`my-agent`** — orchestrator + worker LLM pattern. Claude Sonnet for planning,
  qwen2.5:7b for sub-tasks. Tool calls via function calling.
- **`my-data-pipeline`** — nightly ETL that pulls from N APIs, normalizes,
  stores in SQLite, embeds into Qdrant.

(Replace these with YOUR actual systems. The more concrete you are, the better
the scorer ranks papers.)

## Active themes (weight scoring up if the paper advances any of these)

Edit this list to match what you actively care about:

- **Self-improving agents** — agents that update their own prompts/skills/tools
  based on feedback.
- **In-context learning + memory** — long-context retrieval, episodic memory.
- **Retrieval-augmented generation** — better retrievers, query rewriting,
  hybrid sparse+dense, embedding choice.
- **Multi-agent coordination** — A2A protocols, role specialization, debate.
- **Tool use** — function calling, MCP-server patterns, error recovery.
- **Schema-constrained generation** — JSON-mode reliability, grammar-constrained
  decoding.
- **Local-LLM optimization** — quantization, KV-cache, speculative decoding,
  LoRA swapping.

## Tech stack (concrete, not aspirational)

- **Models**: list what you actually run locally (e.g. qwen2.5:7b, llama3.2:3b,
  nomic-embed-text)
- **Frontier APIs**: which paid APIs you use, if any
- **Infra**: Ollama at 127.0.0.1:11434, Qdrant for vectors, etc.

## What to score LOW (despite high citations)

- Pure theoretical results with no implementation guidance.
- Hardware-specific work (training from scratch at >100B scale).
- Vision-only / robotics work that doesn't transfer to your stack.
- Survey papers without new techniques.

## What to score HIGH

- Drop-in techniques with released code.
- Improvements specifically targeting one of your system slugs above.
- Anything that lets a smaller local model approximate a frontier one.
- New schema-constrained generation tricks.
- Self-improving agent loops with concrete eval results.
